# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ecc-memory-embedded
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Typically, ECC memory maintains a memory system immune to single-bit errors: the data that is read from each word is always the same as the data that had been written to it, even if one of the bits actually stored has been flipped to the wrong state.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Most non-ECC memory cannot detect errors, although some non-ECC memory with parity support allows detection but not correction.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] ECC memory is used in most computers where data corruption cannot be tolerated, like industrial control applications, critical databases, and infrastructural memory caches.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Error correction codes protect against undetected data corruption and are used in computers where such corruption is unacceptable, examples being scientific and financial computing applications, or in database and file servers.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] ECC can also reduce the number of crashes in multi-user server applications and maximum-availability systems.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Electrical or magnetic interference inside a computer system can cause a single bit of dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) to spontaneously flip to the opposite state.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Hence, the error rates increase rapidly with rising altitude; for example, compared to sea level, the rate of neutron flux is 3.5 times higher at 1.5 km and 300 times higher at 10–12 km (the cruising altitude of commercial airplanes).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] As a result, systems operating at high altitudes require special provisions for reliability.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] As an example, the spacecraft *Cassini–Huygens*, launched in 1997, contained two identical flight recorders, each with 2.5 gigabits of memory in the form of arrays of commercial DRAM chips.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Due to built-in EDAC functionality, the spacecraft's engineering telemetry reported the number of (correctable) single-bit-per-word errors and (uncorrectable) double-bit-per-word errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] During the first 2.5 years of flight, the spacecraft reported a nearly constant single-bit error rate of about 280 errors per day.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] However, on November 6, 1997, during the first month in space, the number of errors increased by more than a factor of four on that single day.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] This was attributed to a solar particle event that had been detected by the satellite GOES 9.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] There was some concern that as DRAM density increases further, and thus the components on chips get smaller, while operating voltages continue to fall, DRAM chips will be affected by such radiation more frequently, since lower-energy particles will be able to change a memory cell's state.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] On the other hand, smaller cells make smaller targets, and moves to technologies such as SOI may make individual cells less susceptible and so counteract, or even reverse, this trend.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Recent studies show that single-event upsets due to cosmic radiation have been dropping dramatically with process geometry, and previous concerns over increasing bit cell error rates are unfounded.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Work published between 2007 and 2009 showed widely varying error rates with over 7 orders of magnitude difference, ranging from 10−10 error/(bit·h), roughly one bit error per hour per gigabyte of memory, to 10−17 error/(bit·h), roughly one bit error per millennium per gigabyte of memory.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] A large-scale study based on Google's very large number of servers was presented at the SIGMETRICS/Performance '09 conference.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The actual error rate found was several orders of magnitude higher than the previous small-scale or laboratory studies, with between 25,000 (2.5×10−11 error/(bit·h)) and 70,000 (7.0×10−11 error/(bit·h), or 1 bit error per gigabyte of RAM per 1.8 hours) errors per billion device hours per megabit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] More than 8% of DIMM memory modules were affected by errors per year.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The consequence of a memory error is system-dependent.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] In systems without ECC, an error can lead either to a crash or to corruption of data; in large-scale production sites, memory errors are one of the most-common hardware causes of machine crashes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Memory errors can cause security vulnerabilities.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] A memory error can have no consequences if it changes a bit which neither causes observable malfunctioning nor affects data used in calculations or saved.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] A 2010 simulation study showed that, for a web browser, only a small fraction of memory errors caused data corruption, although, as many memory errors are intermittent and correlated, the effects of memory errors were greater than would be expected for independent soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Some tests conclude that the isolation of DRAM memory cells can be circumvented by unintended side effects of specially crafted accesses to adjacent cells.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Thus, accessing data stored in DRAM causes memory cells to leak their charges and interact electrically, as a result of high cell density in modern memory, altering the content of nearby memory rows that actually were not addressed in the original memory access.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] This effect is known as row hammer, and it has also been used in some privilege escalation computer security exploits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Several approaches have been developed to deal with unwanted bit-flips, including immunity-aware programming, RAM parity memory, and ECC memory.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] This problem can be mitigated by using DRAM modules that include extra memory bits and memory controllers that exploit these bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] These extra bits are used to record parity or to use an error-correcting code (ECC).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Parity allows the detection of all single-bit errors (actually, any odd number of wrong bits), but not correction, so the system has to either carry on (just flagging the problem) or halt.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Error-correction codes allow for more errors to be corrected; how much depends on the exact type of memory used.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] DRAM memory may provide increased protection against soft errors by relying on error-correcting codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Such error-correcting memory, known as *ECC* or *EDAC-protected* memory, is particularly desirable for highly fault-tolerant applications, such as servers, as well as deep-space applications due to increased radiation.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Some systems also "scrub" the memory, by periodically reading all addresses and writing back corrected versions if necessary to remove accumulated soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Many early implementations of ECC memory, as well as on-die ECC, mask correctable errors, acting "as if" the error never occurred, and only report uncorrectable errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Modern implementations log both correctable errors (CE) and uncorrectable errors (UE).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Some people proactively replace memory modules that exhibit high error rates, in order to reduce the likelihood of uncorrectable error events.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Standard server memory are designed for a single-error correction and double-error detection (SECDED) Hamming code, which allows a single-bit error to be corrected and double-bit errors to be detected per word (the unit of bus transfer).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Since DDR SDRAM, the standard bus width (word size) as far as memory is concerned is 64 bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] As a result, the typical setup between DDR and DDR4 is a 72-bit word with 64 data bits and 8 checking bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] DDR5 SDRAM splits the bus into two somewhat independent 32-bit subchannels, so ECC memory uses 80 bits of width in total, split between two 40-bit (32 data, 8 checking) channels.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] ECC is also used with smaller and larger sizes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] An ECC-capable memory controller uses the additional bits to store the SECDED code; the memory is only responsible for holding the extra bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Since the late 1990s, the memory controller also communicates to the BIOS and maintains a count of errors detected and corrected, in part to help identify failing memory modules before the problem becomes catastrophic.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Reading the counter is supported on many systems thanks to the SMBIOS standard, being available on Linux, BSD, and Windows (Windows 2000 and later).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Error detection and correction depends on an expectation of the kinds of errors that occur.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Implicitly, it is assumed that the failure of each bit in a word of memory is independent, resulting in improbability of two simultaneous errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] This used to be the case when memory chips were one-bit wide, what was typical in the first half of the 1980s; later developments moved many bits into the same chip.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] This weakness is addressed by various technologies, including IBM's Chipkill, Sun Microsystems' Extended ECC, Hewlett-Packard's Chipspare, and Intel's Single Device Data Correction (SDDC), all of which make sure that the failure of one memory chip would only affect one bit per ECC word.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] This is achieved by scattering the bits of ECC words across chips, a form of interleaving.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] To make sure each chip only gets one bit per word, it may be necessary to interleave across multiple memory modules (sticks).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Interleaving in general is a useful technique to defend against correlated multi-bit failures.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] A cosmic ray, for example, may upset multiple physically neighboring bits across multiple words by associating neighboring bits to different words.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] As long as a single-event upset (SEU) does not exceed the error threshold (e.g., a single error) in any particular word between accesses, it can be corrected (e.g., by a single-bit error-correcting code), and an effectively error-free memory system may be maintained.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Some DRAM chips include internal "on-chip" or "on-die" error-correction circuits, which allow systems with non-ECC memory controllers to still gain most of the benefits of ECC memory.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] In some systems, a similar effect may be achieved by using EOS memory modules.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] As mentioned above, on-die ECC is mandatory on DDR5 and LPDDR6.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] However, its lack of reporting means that very little is known about the true state of the memory chip until the errors exceed the ability for the on-die algorithm to perform correction; no information on how much "margin" there is conveyed.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Sophisticated algorithms have been built to infer the existence of corrected errors based on non-corrected errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Many ECC memory systems use an "external" EDAC circuit between the CPU and the memory.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] A few systems with ECC memory use both internal and external EDAC systems; the external EDAC system should be designed to correct certain errors that the internal EDAC system is unable to correct.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Modern desktop and server CPUs integrate the EDAC circuit into the CPU, even before the shift toward CPU-integrated memory controllers, which are related to the NUMA architecture.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] CPU integration enables a zero-penalty EDAC system during error-free operation.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] As of 2009, the most-common error-correction codes use Hamming or Hsiao codes that provide single-bit error correction and double-bit error detection (SEC-DED).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Other error-correction codes have been proposed for protecting memory – double-bit error correcting and triple-bit error detecting (DEC-TED) codes, single-nibble error correcting and double-nibble error detecting (SNC-DND) codes, Reed–Solomon error correction codes, etc.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] However, in practice, multi-bit correction is usually implemented by interleaving multiple SEC-DED codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Early research attempted to minimize the area and delay overheads of ECC circuits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Hamming first demonstrated that SEC-DED codes were possible with one particular check matrix.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Hsiao showed that an alternative matrix with odd-weight columns provides SEC-DED capability with less hardware area and shorter delay than traditional Hamming SEC-DED codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] More recent research also attempts to minimize power in addition to minimizing area and delay.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Error-correcting memory controllers traditionally use space-optimal error-correction codes such as Hamming and Hsiao.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] If cost and space is not a concern but speed is, a triple modular redundancy (TMR) may be used due for its faster hardware implementation.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Space satellite systems often use TMR, although satellite RAM usually uses Hamming error correction.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Seymour Cray famously said "parity is for farmers" when asked why he left this out of the CDC 6600.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Later, he included parity in the CDC 7600, which caused pundits to remark that "apparently a lot of farmers buy computers".
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The original IBM PC and all PCs until the early 1990s used parity checking.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Most data paths on a 2020s personal computer, including PCIe, SATA, chip-to-chip interconnection, and on-disk storage, have some form of ECC protection.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The lack of ECC on main memory is in comparison unusual, especially given the size and higher likelihood of corruption.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Linus Torvalds wrote a long post in a forum in 2021 attacking Intel's choice to forgo ECC support on desktop platforms, when contemporary AMD desktop platforms could use (but not necessary enable the ECC feature on) registered DIMMs with ECC support.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Many CPUs use error-correction codes in the on-chip cache, including the Intel Itanium, Xeon, Core and Pentium (since P6 microarchitecture) processors, the AMD Athlon, Opteron, all Zen- and Zen+-based processors (EPYC, EPYC Embedded, Ryzen and Ryzen Threadripper), and the DEC Alpha 21264.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] As of 2006, EDC/ECC and ECC/ECC are the two most-common cache error-protection techniques used in commercial microprocessors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The EDC/ECC technique uses an error-detecting code (EDC) in the level 1 cache.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] If an error is detected, data is recovered from ECC-protected level 2 cache.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The ECC/ECC technique uses an ECC-protected level 1 cache and an ECC-protected level 2 cache.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] CPUs that use the EDC/ECC technique always write-through all STOREs to the level 2 cache, so that when an error is detected during a read from the level 1 data cache, a copy of that data can be recovered from the level 2 cache.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Registered, or buffered, memory is not the same as ECC; the technologies perform different functions.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] It is usual for memory used in servers to be both registered, to allow many memory modules to be used without electrical problems, and ECC, for data integrity.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The use of ECC to increase data security often comes with a bigger expense, resulting in a marginally slower performance and higher memory costs.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] ECC memory is more expensive than non-ECC memory due to its additional error-checking functionality.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The added extra cost of ECC memory for 1 GB in 2010 varies between $0 and $15, depending on performance and manufacturer.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The design of ECC and its purpose in high-reliability workloads positioned it to have additional overhead for validation and the added extra circuit-level designs within the memory.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] The said features typically result in higher costs for the implementation of ECC.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Motherboard manufacturers may choose to add ECC compatibility of varying levels depending on the market segment.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] Some ECC-enabled boards and processors are able to support unbuffered (unregistered) ECC, but will also work with non-ECC memory; system firmware enables ECC functionality if ECC memory is installed.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] ECC may lower memory performance by around 2–3 percent on some systems, depending on the application and implementation, due to the additional time needed for ECC memory controllers to perform error checking.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/ecc-memory] However, modern systems integrate ECC testing into the CPU, generating no additional delay to memory accesses as long as no errors are detected.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In computing, telecommunication, information theory, and coding theory, **forward error correction** (**FEC**) or **channel coding** is a technique used for controlling errors in data transmission over unreliable or noisy communication channels.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The central idea is that the sender encodes the message in a redundant way, most often by using an **error correction code**, or **error correcting code** (**ECC**).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The redundancy allows the receiver not only to detect errors that may occur anywhere in the message, but often to correct a limited number of errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Therefore a reverse channel to request re-transmission may not be needed.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The cost is a fixed, higher forward channel bandwidth.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The American mathematician Richard Hamming pioneered this field in the 1940s and invented the first error-correcting code in 1950: the Hamming (7,4) code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] FEC can be applied in situations where re-transmissions are costly or impossible, such as one-way communication links or when transmitting to multiple receivers in multicast.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Long-latency connections also benefit; in the case of satellites orbiting distant planets, retransmission due to errors would create a delay of several hours.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] FEC is also widely used in modems and in cellular networks.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] FEC processing in a receiver may be applied to a digital bit stream or in the demodulation of a digitally modulated carrier.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] For the latter, FEC is an integral part of the initial analog-to-digital conversion in the receiver.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The Viterbi decoder implements a soft-decision algorithm to demodulate digital data from an analog signal corrupted by noise.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Many FEC decoders can also generate a bit-error rate (BER) signal which can be used as feedback to fine-tune the analog receiving electronics.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] FEC information is added to mass storage (magnetic, optical and solid state/flash based) devices to enable recovery of corrupted data, and is used as ECC computer memory on systems that require special provisions for reliability.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The maximum proportion of errors or missing bits that can be corrected is determined by the design of the ECC, so different forward error correcting codes are suitable for different conditions.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In general, a stronger code induces more redundancy that needs to be transmitted using the available bandwidth, which reduces the effective bit-rate while improving the received effective signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The noisy-channel coding theorem of Claude Shannon can be used to compute the maximum achievable communication bandwidth for a given maximum acceptable error probability.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] This establishes bounds on the theoretical maximum information transfer rate of a channel with some given base noise level.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] However, the proof is not constructive, and hence gives no insight of how to build a capacity achieving code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] After years of research, some advanced FEC systems like polar code come very close to the theoretical maximum (Shannon limit) given by the Shannon channel capacity under the hypothesis of an infinite length frame.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] ECC is accomplished by adding redundancy to the transmitted information using an algorithm.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] A redundant bit may be a complicated function of many original information bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The original information may or may not appear literally in the encoded output; codes that include the unmodified input in the output are **systematic**, while those that do not are **non-systematic**.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] A simplistic example of ECC is to transmit each data bit three times, which is known as a (3,1) repetition code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Through a noisy channel, a receiver might see eight versions of the output; see the table below.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] This allows an error in any one of the three samples to be corrected by "majority vote" or "democratic voting".
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Though simple to implement and widely used, this triple modular redundancy is a relatively inefficient ECC.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Better ECC codes typically examine the last several tens or even the last several hundreds of previously received bits to determine how to decode the current small handful of bits (typically in groups of two to eight bits).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Most commonly, f is a homomorphism in the sense that if $x_{1}*x_{2}$ is the concatenation of $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ , then we have the following: $f(u_{1}*u_{2})=f(u_{1})*f(u_{2})$ This implies that it is enough to define $f(\sigma )$ for single-letter words $\sigma$ .
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] A code with distance d can detect errors on k bits as long as $k<d$ , and among those detected errors, the code can correct l -bit errors whenever $2l<d$ .
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] ECC could be said to work by "averaging noise"; since each data bit affects many transmitted symbols, the corruption of some symbols by noise usually allows the original user data to be extracted from the other, uncorrupted received symbols that also depend on the same user data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Most telecommunication systems use a fixed channel code designed to tolerate the expected worst-case bit error rate, and then fail to work at all if the bit error rate is ever worse.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The two main categories of ECC codes are block codes and convolutional codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Classical block codes are usually decoded using **hard-decision** algorithms, which means that for every input and output signal a hard decision is made whether it corresponds to a one or a zero bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In contrast, convolutional codes are typically decoded using **soft-decision** algorithms like the Viterbi, MAP or BCJR algorithms, which process (discretized) analog signals, and which allow for much higher error-correction performance than hard-decision decoding.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Nearly all classical block codes apply the algebraic properties of finite fields.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Hence classical block codes are often referred to as algebraic codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] There are many types of block codes; Reed–Solomon coding is noteworthy for its widespread use in compact discs, DVDs, and hard disk drives.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Other examples of classical block codes include Golay, BCH, Multidimensional parity, and Hamming codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Hamming ECC is commonly used to correct ECC memory and early SLC NAND flash memory errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] This provides single-bit error correction and 2-bit error detection.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Hamming codes are only suitable for more reliable single-level cell (SLC) NAND.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Denser multi-level cell (MLC) NAND may use multi-bit correcting ECC such as BCH, Reed–Solomon, or LDPC.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] NOR flash typically does not use any error correction.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Low-density parity-check (LDPC) codes are a class of highly efficient linear block codes made from many single parity check (SPC) codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] They can provide performance very close to the channel capacity (the theoretical maximum) using an iterated soft-decision decoding approach, at linear time complexity in terms of their block length.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Practical implementations rely heavily on decoding the constituent SPC codes in parallel.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] LDPC codes were first introduced by Robert G.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Gallager in his PhD thesis in 1960, but due to the computational effort in implementing encoder and decoder and the introduction of Reed–Solomon codes, they were mostly ignored until the 1990s.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Other LDPC codes are standardized for wireless communication standards within 3GPP MBMS (see fountain codes).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Turbo coding is an iterated soft-decoding scheme that combines two or more relatively simple convolutional codes and an interleaver to produce a block code that can perform to within a fraction of a decibel of the Shannon limit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Predating LDPC codes in terms of practical application, they now provide similar performance.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] One of the earliest commercial applications of turbo coding was the CDMA2000 1x (TIA IS-2000) digital cellular technology developed by Qualcomm and sold by Verizon Wireless, Sprint, and other carriers.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] It is also used for the evolution of CDMA2000 1x specifically for Internet access, 1xEV-DO (TIA IS-856).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Like 1x, EV-DO was developed by Qualcomm, and is sold by Verizon Wireless, Sprint, and other carriers (Verizon's marketing name for 1xEV-DO is *Broadband Access*, Sprint's consumer and business marketing names for 1xEV-DO are *Power Vision* and *Mobile Broadband*, respectively).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In contrast to classical block codes that often specify an error-detecting or error-correcting ability, many modern block codes such as LDPC codes lack such guarantees.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Instead, modern codes are evaluated in terms of their bit error rates.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Most forward error correction codes correct only bit-flips, but not bit-insertions or bit-deletions.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In this setting, the Hamming distance is the appropriate way to measure the bit error rate.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] A few forward error correction codes are designed to correct bit-insertions and bit-deletions, such as Marker Codes and Watermark Codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The Levenshtein distance is a more appropriate way to measure the bit error rate when using such codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The fundamental principle of ECC is to add redundant bits in order to help the decoder to find out the true message that was encoded by the transmitter.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The code-rate of a given ECC system is defined as the ratio between the number of information bits and the total number of bits (i.e., information plus redundancy bits) in a given communication package.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] A low code-rate close to zero implies a strong code that uses many redundant bits to achieve a good performance, while a large code-rate close to 1 implies a weak code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The redundant bits that protect the information have to be transferred using the same communication resources that they are trying to protect.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] This causes a fundamental tradeoff between reliability and data rate.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In one extreme, a strong code (with low code-rate) can induce an important increase in the receiver SNR (signal-to-noise-ratio) decreasing the bit error rate, at the cost of reducing the effective data rate.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] On the other extreme, not using any ECC (i.e., a code-rate equal to 1) uses the full channel for information transfer purposes, at the cost of leaving the bits without any additional protection.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] One interesting question is the following: how efficient in terms of information transfer can an ECC be that has a negligible decoding error rate?
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] This question was answered by Claude Shannon with his second theorem, which says that the channel capacity is the maximum bit rate achievable by any ECC whose error rate tends to zero: His proof relies on Gaussian random coding, which is not suitable to real-world applications.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The upper bound given by Shannon's work inspired a long journey in designing ECCs that can come close to the ultimate performance boundary.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Various codes today can attain almost the Shannon limit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] However, capacity achieving ECCs are usually extremely complex to implement.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The most popular ECCs have a trade-off between performance and computational complexity.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Usually, their parameters give a range of possible code rates, which can be optimized depending on the scenario.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Usually, this optimization is done in order to achieve a low decoding error probability while minimizing the impact to the data rate.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Another criterion for optimizing the code rate is to balance low error rate and retransmissions number in order to the energy cost of the communication.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Sometimes it is only necessary to decode single bits of the message, or to check whether a given signal is a codeword, and do so without looking at the entire signal.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] This can make sense in a streaming setting, where codewords are too large to be classically decoded fast enough and where only a few bits of the message are of interest for now.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Also such codes have become an important tool in computational complexity theory, e.g., for the design of probabilistically checkable proofs.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Locally decodable codes are error-correcting codes for which single bits of the message can be probabilistically recovered by only looking at a small (say constant) number of positions of a codeword, even after the codeword has been corrupted at some constant fraction of positions.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Locally testable codes are error-correcting codes for which it can be checked probabilistically whether a signal is close to a codeword by only looking at a small number of positions of the signal.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Not all locally decodable codes (LDCs) are locally testable codes (LTCs) neither locally correctable codes (LCCs), q-query LCCs are bounded exponentially while LDCs can have subexponential lengths.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Single pass decoding with this family of error correction codes can yield very low error rates, but for long range transmission conditions (like deep space) iterative decoding is recommended.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Concatenated codes have been standard practice in satellite and deep space communications since Voyager 2 first used the technique in its 1986 encounter with Uranus.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The Galileo craft used iterative concatenated codes to compensate for the very high error rate conditions caused by having a failed antenna.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Interleaving is frequently used in digital communication and storage systems to improve the performance of forward error correcting codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Many communication channels are not memoryless: errors typically occur in bursts rather than independently.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] If the number of errors within a code word exceeds the error-correcting code's capability, it fails to recover the original code word.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Interleaving alleviates this problem by shuffling source symbols across several code words, thereby creating a more uniform distribution of errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Therefore, interleaving is widely used for burst error-correction.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The analysis of modern iterated codes, like turbo codes and LDPC codes, typically assumes an independent distribution of errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Systems using LDPC codes therefore typically employ additional interleaving across the symbols within a code word.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] For turbo codes, an interleaver is an integral component and its proper design is crucial for good performance.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The iterative decoding algorithm works best when there are not short cycles in the factor graph that represents the decoder; the interleaver is chosen to avoid short cycles.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In multi-carrier communication systems, interleaving across carriers may be employed to provide frequency diversity, e.g., to mitigate frequency-selective fading or narrowband interference.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Here, each group of the same letter represents a 4-bit one-bit error-correcting codeword.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The codeword cccc is altered in one bit and can be corrected, but the codeword dddd is altered in three bits, so either it cannot be decoded at all or it might be decoded incorrectly.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In each of the codewords "aaaa", "eeee", "ffff", and "gggg", only one bit is altered, so one-bit error-correcting code will decode everything correctly.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The term "AnExample" ends up mostly unintelligible and difficult to correct.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] No word is completely lost and the missing letters can be recovered with minimal guesswork.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Use of interleaving techniques increases total delay.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] This is because the entire interleaved block must be received before the packets can be decoded.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Also interleavers hide the structure of errors; without an interleaver, more advanced decoding algorithms can take advantage of the error structure and achieve more reliable communication than a simpler decoder combined with an interleaver.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] An example of such an algorithm is based on neural network structures.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] Simulating the behaviour of error-correcting codes (ECCs) in software is a common practice to design, validate and improve ECCs.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The upcoming wireless 5G standard raises a new range of applications for the software ECCs: the Cloud Radio Access Networks (C-RAN) in a Software-defined radio (SDR) context.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] The idea is to directly use software ECCs in the communications.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] For instance in the 5G, the software ECCs could be located in the cloud and the antennas connected to this computing resources: improving this way the flexibility of the communication network and eventually increasing the energy efficiency of the system.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In this context, there are various available Open-source software listed below (non exhaustive).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/error-correction-code] In the table above, for an error-correcting code of minimal Hamming distance d , the maximum number of errors that the code can detect is given by $d-1$ while the maximal number of errors that it can correct is given by $\left\lfloor {\frac {d-1}{2}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In computer science and telecommunications, **Hamming codes** are a family of linear error-correcting codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming codes can detect one-bit and two-bit errors, or correct one-bit errors without detection of uncorrected errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] By contrast, the simple parity code cannot correct errors, and can detect only an odd number of bits in error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming codes are perfect codes, that is, they achieve the highest possible rate for codes with their block length and minimum distance of three.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming invented Hamming codes in 1950 as a way of automatically correcting errors introduced by punched card readers.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In his original paper, Hamming elaborated his general idea, but specifically focused on the Hamming(7,4) code which adds three parity bits to four bits of data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In mathematical terms, Hamming codes are a class of binary linear codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] For each integer *r* ≥ 2 there is a code-word with block length *n* = 2*r* − 1 and message length *k* = 2*r* − *r* − 1.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hence the rate of Hamming codes is *R* = *k* / *n* = 1 − *r* / (2*r* − 1), which is the highest possible for codes with minimum distance of three (i.e., the minimal number of bit changes needed to go from any code word to any other code word is three) and block length 2*r* − 1.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The parity-check matrix of a Hamming code is constructed by listing all columns of length *r* that are non-zero, which means that the dual code of the Hamming code is the shortened Hadamard code, also known as a Simplex code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The parity-check matrix has the property that any two columns are pairwise linearly independent.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Due to the limited redundancy that Hamming codes add to the data, they can only detect and correct errors when the error rate is low.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] This is the case in computer memory (usually RAM), where bit errors are extremely rare and Hamming codes are widely used.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Memory with this correction system is known as ECC memory.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In this context, an extended Hamming code having one extra parity bit is often used.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Extended Hamming codes achieve a Hamming distance of four, which allows the decoder to distinguish between when at most one one-bit error occurs and when any two-bit errors occur.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In this sense, extended Hamming codes are single-error correcting and double-error detecting, abbreviated as **SECDED**.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Richard Hamming, the inventor of Hamming codes, worked at Bell Labs in the late 1940s on the Bell Model V computer, an electromechanical relay-based machine with cycle times in seconds.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Input was fed in on punched paper tape, seven-eighths of an inch wide, which had up to six holes per row.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] During weekdays, when errors in the relays were detected, the machine would stop and flash lights so that the operators could correct the problem.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] During after-hours periods and on weekends, when there were no operators, the machine simply moved on to the next job.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming worked on weekends, and grew increasingly frustrated with having to restart his programs from scratch due to detected errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In a taped interview, Hamming said, "And so I said, 'Damn it, if the machine can detect an error, why can't it locate the position of the error and correct it?'".
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Over the next few years, he worked on the problem of error-correction, developing an increasingly powerful array of algorithms.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In 1950, he published what is now known as Hamming code, which remains in use today in applications such as ECC memory.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] A number of simple error-detecting codes were used before Hamming codes, but none were as effective as Hamming codes in the same overhead of space.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Parity adds a single bit that indicates whether the number of ones (bit-positions with values of one) in the preceding data was even or odd.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If an odd number of bits is changed in transmission, the message will change parity and the error can be detected at this point; however, the bit that changed may have been the parity bit itself.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The most common convention is that a parity value of one indicates that there is an odd number of ones in the data, and a parity value of zero indicates that there is an even number of ones.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the number of bits changed is even, the check bit will be valid and the error will not be detected.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Moreover, parity does not indicate which bit contained the error, even when it can detect it.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The data must be discarded entirely and re-transmitted from scratch.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] On a noisy transmission medium, a successful transmission could take a long time or may never occur.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] However, while the quality of parity checking is poor, since it uses only a single bit, this method results in the least overhead.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] A two-out-of-five code is an encoding scheme which uses five bits consisting of exactly three 0s and two 1s.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] This provides ${\binom {5}{3}}=10$ possible combinations, enough to represent the digits 0–9.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] This scheme can detect all single bit-errors, all odd numbered bit-errors and some even numbered bit-errors (for example the flipping of both 1-bits).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] However it still cannot correct any of these errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Another code in use at the time repeated every data bit multiple times in order to ensure that it was sent correctly.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] For instance, if the data bit to be sent is a 1, an *n* = 3 *repetition code* will send 111.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the three bits received are not identical, an error occurred during transmission.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the channel is clean enough, most of the time only one bit will change in each triple.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Therefore, 001, 010, and 100 each correspond to a 0 bit, while 110, 101, and 011 correspond to a 1 bit, with the greater quantity of digits that are the same ('0' or a '1') indicating what the data bit should be.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] A code with this ability to reconstruct the original message in the presence of errors is known as an *error-correcting* code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] This triple repetition code is a Hamming code with *m* = 2, since there are two parity bits, and 22 − 2 − 1 = 1 data bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Such codes cannot correctly repair all errors, however.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In our example, if the channel flips two bits and the receiver gets 001, the system will detect the error, but conclude that the original bit is 0, which is incorrect.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If we increase the size of the bit string to four, we can detect all two-bit errors but cannot correct them (the quantity of parity bits is even); at five bits, we can both detect and correct all two-bit errors, but not all three-bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Moreover, increasing the size of the parity bit string is inefficient, reducing throughput by three times in our original case, and the efficiency drops drastically as we increase the number of times each bit is duplicated in order to detect and correct more errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If more error-correcting bits are included with a message, and if those bits can be arranged such that different incorrect bits produce different error results, then bad bits could be identified.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In a seven-bit message, there are seven possible single bit errors, so three error control bits could potentially specify not only that an error occurred but also which bit caused the error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming studied the existing coding schemes, including two-of-five, and generalized their concepts.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] To start with, he developed a nomenclature to describe the system, including the number of data bits and error-correction bits in a block.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] For instance, parity includes a single bit for any data word, so assuming ASCII words with seven bits, Hamming described this as an *(8,7)* code, with eight bits in total, of which seven are data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The repetition example would be *(3,1)*, following the same logic.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The code rate is the second number divided by the first, for our repetition example, 1/3.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming also noticed the problems with flipping two or more bits, and described this as the "distance" (it is now called the *Hamming distance*, after him).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Parity has a distance of 2, so one bit flip can be detected but not corrected, and any two bit flips will be invisible.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The (3,1) repetition has a distance of 3, as three bits need to be flipped in the same triple to obtain another code word with no visible errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] It can correct one-bit errors or it can detect - but not correct - two-bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] A (4,1) repetition (each bit is repeated four times) has a distance of 4, so flipping three bits can be detected, but not corrected.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] When three bits flip in the same group there can be situations where attempting to correct will produce the wrong code word.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In general, a code with distance *k* can detect but not correct *k* − 1 errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming was interested in two problems at once: increasing the distance as much as possible, while at the same time increasing the code rate as much as possible.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] During the 1940s he developed several encoding schemes that were dramatic improvements on existing codes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The key to all of his systems was to have the parity bits overlap, such that they managed to check each other as well as the data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The following general algorithm generates a single-error correcting (SEC) code for any number of bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The main idea is to choose the error-correcting bits such that the index-XOR (the XOR of all the bit positions containing a 1) is 0.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] (in binary) as the error-correcting bits, which guarantees it is possible to set the error-correcting bits so that the index-XOR of the whole message is 0.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the receiver receives a string with index-XOR 0, they can conclude there were no corruptions, and otherwise, the index-XOR indicates the index of the corrupted bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] All bit positions that are powers of two (have a single 1 bit in the binary form of their position) are parity bits: 1, 2, 4, 8, etc.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] All other bit positions, with two or more 1 bits in the binary form of their position, are data bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Each data bit is included in a unique set of 2 or more parity bits, as determined by the binary form of its bit position.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Parity bit 2 covers all bit positions which have the **second** least significant bit set: bits 2–3, 6–7, 10–11, etc.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Parity bit 4 covers all bit positions which have the **third** least significant bit set: bits 4–7, 12–15, 20–23, etc.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Parity bit 8 covers all bit positions which have the **fourth** least significant bit set: bits 8–15, 24–31, 40–47, etc.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In general each parity bit covers all bits where the bitwise AND of the parity position and the bit position is non-zero.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If a byte of data to be encoded is 10011010, then the data word (using _ to represent the parity bits) would be __1_001_1010, and the code word is 011100101010.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The choice of the parity, even or odd, is irrelevant but the same choice must be used for both encoding and decoding.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Shown are only 20 encoded bits (5 parity, 15 data) but the pattern continues indefinitely.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The key thing about Hamming codes that can be seen from visual inspection is that any given bit is included in a unique set of parity bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] To check for errors, check all of the parity bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The pattern of errors, called the error syndrome, identifies the bit in error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If all parity bits are correct, there is no error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Otherwise, the sum of the positions of the erroneous parity bits identifies the erroneous bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] For example, if the parity bits in positions 1, 2 and 8 indicate an error, then bit 1+2+8=11 is in error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If only one parity bit indicates an error, the parity bit itself is in error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] With m parity bits, bits from 1 up to $2^{m}-1$ can be covered.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] After discounting the parity bits, $2^{m}-m-1$ bits remain for use as data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Hamming codes have a minimum distance of 3, which means that the decoder can detect and correct a single error, but it cannot distinguish a double bit error of some codeword from a single bit error of a different codeword.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Thus, some double-bit errors will be incorrectly decoded as if they were single bit errors and therefore go undetected, unless no correction is attempted.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] To remedy this shortcoming, Hamming codes can be extended by an extra parity bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] This way, it is possible to increase the minimum distance of the Hamming code to 4, which allows the decoder to distinguish between single bit errors and two-bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Thus the decoder can detect and correct a single error and at the same time detect (but not correct) a double error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the decoder does not attempt to correct errors, it can reliably detect triple bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the decoder does correct errors, some triple errors will be mistaken for single errors and "corrected" to the wrong value.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Error correction is therefore a trade-off between certainty (the ability to reliably detect triple bit errors) and resiliency (the ability to keep functioning in the face of single bit errors).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] This extended Hamming code was popular in computer memory systems, starting with IBM 7030 Stretch in 1961, where it is known as *SECDED* (or SEC-DED, abbreviated from *single error correction, double error detection*).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Common forms for memory systems include (39,32) and (72,64).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The (72,64) Hamming code is still popular in some hardware designs, including Xilinx FPGA families.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] In 1950, Hamming introduced the [7,4] Hamming code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] It encodes four data bits into seven bits by adding three parity bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] As explained earlier, it can either detect and correct single-bit errors or it can detect (but not correct) both single and double-bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] With the addition of an overall parity bit, it becomes the [8,4] extended Hamming code and can both detect and correct single-bit errors and detect (but not correct) double-bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] and $\mathbf {H} :={\begin{pmatrix}{\begin{array}{c|c}A&I_{n-k}\\\end{array}}\end{pmatrix}}$ is called a parity-check matrix.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] This is the construction of **G** and **H** in standard (or systematic) form.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The parity-check matrix **H** of a Hamming code is constructed by listing all columns of length *m* that are pair-wise independent.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Thus **H** is a matrix whose left side is all of the nonzero *n*-tuples where order of the *n*-tuples in the columns of matrix does not matter.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The right hand side is just the (*n* − *k*)-identity matrix.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] So **G** can be obtained from **H** by taking the transpose of the left hand side of **H** with the identity *k*-identity matrix on the left hand side of **G**.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] From the above matrix we have 2k = 24 = 16 codewords.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The codeword ${\vec {x}}$ for any of the 16 possible data vectors ${\vec {a}}$ is given by the standard matrix product ${\vec {x}}={\vec {a}}G$ where the summing operation is done modulo-2.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The [7,4] Hamming code can easily be extended to an [8,4] code by adding an extra parity bit on top of the (7,4) encoded word (see Hamming(7,4)).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] For example, the first row in this matrix is the sum of the second and third rows of H in non-systematic form.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The non-systematic form of G can be row reduced (using elementary row operations) to match this matrix.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The addition of the fourth row effectively computes the sum of all the codeword bits (data and parity) as the fourth parity bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] For example, 1011 is encoded (using the non-systematic form of G at the start of this section) into 01100110 where blue digits are data; red digits are parity bits from the [7,4] Hamming code; and the green digit is the parity bit added by the [8,4] code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] The green digit makes the parity of the [7,4] codewords even.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Finally, it can be shown that the minimum distance has increased from 3, in the [7,4] code, to 4 in the [8,4] code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Therefore, the code can be defined as [8,4] Hamming code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] To decode the [8,4] Hamming code, first check the parity bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the parity bit indicates an error, single error correction (the [7,4] Hamming code) will indicate the error location, with "no error" indicating the parity bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the parity bit is correct, then single error correction will indicate the (bitwise) exclusive-or of two error locations.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] If the locations are equal ("no error") then a double bit error either has not occurred, or has cancelled itself out.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/hamming-code] Otherwise, a double bit error has occurred.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] A **parity bit**, or **check bit**, is a bit added to a string of binary code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity bits are a simple form of error detecting code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity bits are generally applied to the smallest units of a communication protocol, typically 8-bit octets (bytes), although they can also be applied separately to an entire message string of bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The parity bit ensures that the total number of 1-bits in the string is even or odd.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Accordingly, there are two variants of parity bits: **even parity bit** and **odd parity bit**.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In the case of even parity, for a given set of bits, the bits whose value is 1 are counted.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] If that count is odd, the parity bit value is set to 1, making the total count of occurrences of 1s in the whole set (including the parity bit) an even number.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] If the count of 1s in a given set of bits is already even, the parity bit's value is 0.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In the case of odd parity, the coding is reversed.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] For a given set of bits, if the count of bits with a value of 1 is even, the parity bit value is set to 1 making the total count of 1s in the whole set (including the parity bit) an odd number.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] If the count of bits with a value of 1 is odd, the count is already odd so the parity bit's value is 0.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity is a special case of a cyclic redundancy check (CRC), where the 1-bit CRC is generated by the polynomial *x*+1.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In mathematics *parity* can refer to the evenness or oddness of an integer, which, when written in its binary form, can be determined just by examining only its least significant bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In information technology parity refers to the evenness or oddness, given any set of binary digits, of the number of those bits with value one.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Because parity is determined by the state of every one of the bits, this property of parity—being dependent upon all the bits and changing its value from even to odd parity if any one bit changes—allows for its use in error detection and correction schemes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In telecommunications the parity referred to by some protocols is for error-*detection*.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The transmission medium is preset, at both end points, to agree on either odd parity or even parity.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] For each string of bits ready to transmit (data packet) the sender calculates its parity bit, zero or one, to make it conform to the agreed parity, even or odd.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The receiver of that packet first checks that the parity of the packet as a whole is in accordance with the preset agreement, then, if there was a parity error in that packet, requests a retransmission of that packet.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In computer science the parity stripe or parity disk in a RAID provides error-*correction*.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity bits are written at the rate of one parity bit per *n* bits, where *n* is the number of disks in the array.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] When a read error occurs, each bit in the error region is recalculated from its set of *n* bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In this way, using one parity bit creates "redundancy" for a region from the size of one bit to the size of one disk.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In electronics, transcoding data with parity can be very efficient, as XOR gates output what is equivalent to a check bit that creates an even parity, and XOR logic design easily scales to any number of inputs.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] XOR and AND structures comprise the bulk of most integrated circuitry.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] If an odd number of bits (including the parity bit) are transmitted incorrectly, the parity bit will be incorrect, thus indicating that a **parity error** occurred in the transmission.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The parity bit is suitable only for detecting errors; it cannot correct any errors, as there is no way to determine the particular bit that is corrupted.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The data must be discarded entirely, and retransmitted from scratch.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] On a noisy transmission medium, successful transmission can therefore take a long time or even never occur.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] However, parity has the advantage that it uses only a single bit and requires only a number of XOR gates to generate.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] See Hamming code for an example of an error-correcting code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity bit checking is used occasionally for transmitting ASCII characters, which have 7 bits, leaving the 8th bit as a parity bit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] For example, the parity bit can be computed as follows.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Assume Alice and Bob are communicating and Alice wants to send Bob the simple 4-bit message 1001.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] This mechanism enables the detection of single bit errors, because if one bit gets flipped due to line noise, there will be an incorrect number of ones in the received data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In the two examples above, Bob's calculated parity value matches the parity bit in its received value, indicating there are no single bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] There is a limitation to parity schemes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] A parity bit is guaranteed to detect only an odd number of bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] If an even number of bits have errors, the parity bit records the correct number of ones even though the data is corrupt.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Bob observes even parity, as expected, thereby failing to catch the two bit errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Because of its simplicity, parity is used in many hardware applications in which an operation can be repeated in case of difficulty, or simply detecting the error is helpful.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] For example, the SCSI and PCI buses use parity to detect transmission errors, and many microprocessor instruction caches include parity protection.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Because the Instruction cache data is just a copy of the main memory, it can be disregarded and refetched if it is found to be corrupted.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In serial data transmission, a common format is 7 data bits, an even parity bit, and one or two stop bits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] That format accommodates all the 7-bit ASCII characters in an 8-bit byte.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Other formats are possible; 8 bits of data plus a parity bit can convey all 8-bit byte values.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Recovery from the error is usually done by retransmitting the data, the details of which are usually handled by software (such as the operating system I/O routines).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] When the total number of transmitted bits, including the parity bit, is even, odd parity has the advantage that both all-zeros and all-ones patterns are detected as errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] If the total number of bits is odd, only one of the patterns is detected as an error, and the choice can be made based on what the more common error is expected to be.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity data is used by RAID arrays (redundant array of independent/inexpensive disks) to achieve redundancy.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] If a drive in the array fails, remaining data on the other drives can be combined with the parity data (using the Boolean XOR function) to reconstruct the missing data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The resulting parity data, **10111001**, is then stored on Drive 3.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Should any of the three drives fail, the contents of the failed drive can be reconstructed on a replacement drive by subjecting the data from the remaining drives to the same XOR operation.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The result of that XOR calculation yields Drive 2's contents.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] **11010100** is then stored on Drive 2, fully repairing the array.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] XOR logic is also equivalent to even parity (because *a* XOR *b* XOR *c* XOR ... may be treated as XOR(*a*,*b*,*c*,...), which is an n-ary operator that is true if and only if an odd number of arguments is true).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] So the same XOR concept above applies similarly to larger RAID arrays with parity, using any number of disks.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In the case of a RAID 3 array of 12 drives, 11 drives participate in the XOR calculation shown above and yield a value that is then stored on the dedicated parity drive.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Extensions and variations on the parity bit mechanism "double," "dual," or "diagonal" parity, are used in RAID-DP.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] A *parity track* was present on the first magnetic-tape data storage in 1951.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity in this form, applied across multiple parallel signals, is known as a transverse redundancy check.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] This can be combined with parity computed over multiple bits sent on a single signal, a longitudinal redundancy check.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] In a parallel bus, there is one longitudinal redundancy check bit per parallel signal.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] Parity was also used on at least some paper-tape (punched tape) data entry systems (which preceded magnetic-tape systems).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] On the systems sold by British company ICL (formerly ICT) the 1-inch-wide (25 mm) paper tape had 8 hole positions running across it, with the 8th being for parity.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] 7 positions were used for the data, e.g., 7-bit ASCII.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/parity-bit] The 8th position had a hole punched in it depending on the number of data holes punched.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] The state change is a result of the free charge created by ionization in or close to an important node of a logic element (e.g. memory "bit").
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] The error in device output or operation caused as a result of the strike is called an SEU or a soft error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] The SEU itself is not considered permanently damaging to the transistors' or circuits' functionality, unlike the case of single-event latch-up (SEL), single-event gate rupture (SEGR), or single-event burnout (SEB).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] These are all examples of a general class of radiation effects in electronic devices called *single-event effects* (SEEs).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Single-event upsets were first described during above-ground nuclear testing, from 1954 to 1957, when many anomalies were observed in electronic monitoring equipment.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Further problems were observed in space electronics during the 1960s, although it was difficult to separate soft failures from other forms of interference.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In 1972, a Hughes satellite experienced an upset where the communication with the satellite was lost for 96 seconds and then recaptured.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Dan Binder explained the anomaly as a single-event upset (SEU) and published the first SEU paper in the *IEEE Transactions on Nuclear Science* journal in 1975.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In 1978, the first evidence of soft errors from alpha particles in packaging materials was described by Timothy C.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In 1979, James Ziegler of IBM, along with W.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Lanford of Yale, first described the mechanism whereby a sea-level cosmic ray could cause a single-event upset in electronics.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] 1979 also saw the world's first heavy ion "single-event effects" test at a particle accelerator facility, conducted at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory's 88-Inch Cyclotron and Bevatron.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Terrestrial SEUs arise due to cosmic particles colliding with atoms in the atmosphere, creating cascades or showers of neutrons and protons, which in turn may interact with electronic circuits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] At deep sub-micron geometries, this affects semiconductor devices in the atmosphere.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In space, high-energy ionizing particles exist as part of the natural background, referred to as galactic cosmic rays (GCRs).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Solar particle events and high-energy protons trapped in the Earth's magnetosphere (Van Allen radiation belts) exacerbate this problem.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] The high energies associated with the phenomenon in the space particle environment generally render increased spacecraft shielding useless in terms of eliminating SEUs and catastrophic single-event phenomena (e.g. destructive latch-up).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Secondary atmospheric neutrons generated by cosmic rays can also have sufficiently high energy for producing SEUs in electronics on aircraft flights over the poles or at high altitudes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Trace amounts of radioactive elements in chip packages also lead to SEUs.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] The sensitivity of a device to SEU can be empirically estimated by placing a test device in a particle stream at a cyclotron or other particle accelerator facility.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] This particular test methodology is especially useful for predicting the SER (soft error rate) in known space environments but can be problematic for estimating terrestrial SER from neutrons.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In this case, a large number of parts must be evaluated, possibly at different altitudes, to find the actual rate of upset.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Another way to empirically estimate SEU tolerance is to use a chamber shielded from radiation, with a known radiation source, such as Caesium-137.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] When testing microprocessors for SEU, the software used to exercise the device must also be evaluated to determine which sections of the device were activated when SEUs occurred.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] By definition, SEUs do not destroy the circuits involved, but they can cause errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In space-based microprocessors, one of the most vulnerable portions is often the 1st and 2nd-level cache memories, because these must be very small and have very high speed, which means that they do not hold much charge.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Often these caches are disabled if terrestrial designs are being configured to survive SEUs.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Another vulnerable processor component is RAM, and more specifically static RAM (SRAM) used in cache memories.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] SRAM memories are usually designed with transistor sizes close to the minimum allowed by technology to allocate the maximum number of bits per unit area.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Small transistor sizes and high bit density make memories one of the most susceptible components to SEUs.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] To ensure resilience to SEUs, often an error correcting memory is used, together with circuitry to periodically read (leading to correction) or scrub (if reading does not lead to correction) the memory of errors, before the errors overwhelm the error-correcting circuitry.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In digital and analog circuits, a single event may cause one or more voltages pulses (i.e. glitches) to propagate through the circuit, in which case it is referred to as a single-event transient (SET).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Since the propagating pulse is not technically a change of "state" as in a memory SEU, one should differentiate between SET and SEU.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] If a SET propagates through digital circuitry and results in an incorrect value being latched in a sequential logic unit, it is then considered an SEU.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Hardware problems can also occur for related reasons.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Under certain circumstances (of both circuit design, process design, and particle properties) a "parasitic" thyristor inherent to CMOS designs can be activated, effectively causing an apparent short-circuit from power to ground.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] This condition is referred to as *latch-up*, and in absence of constructional countermeasures, often destroys the device due to thermal runaway.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] Most manufacturers design to prevent latch-up and test their products to ensure that latch-up does not occur from atmospheric particle strikes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/single-event-upset] In order to prevent latch-up in space, epitaxial substrates, silicon on insulator (SOI) or silicon on sapphire (SOS) are often used to further reduce or eliminate the susceptibility.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In electronics and computing, a **soft error** is a type of error where a signal or datum is wrong.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Errors may be caused by a defect, usually understood either to be a mistake in design or construction, or a broken component.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] A soft error is also a signal or datum which is wrong, but is not assumed to imply such a mistake or breakage.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] After observing a soft error, there is no implication that the system is any less reliable than before.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] One cause of soft errors is single event upsets from cosmic rays.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In a computer's memory system, a soft error changes an instruction in a program or a data value.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft errors typically can be remedied by cold booting the computer.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] A soft error will not damage a system's hardware; the only damage is to the data that is being processed.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] There are two types of soft errors, *chip-level soft error* and *system-level soft error*.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Chip-level soft errors occur when particles hit the chip, e.g., when secondary particles from cosmic rays land on the silicon die.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] If a particle with certain properties hits a memory cell it can cause the cell to change state to a different value.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The atomic reaction in this example is so tiny that it does not damage the physical structure of the chip.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] System-level soft errors occur when the data being processed is hit with a noise phenomenon, typically when the data is on a data bus.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The computer tries to interpret the noise as a data bit, which can cause errors in addressing or processing program code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The bad data bit can even be saved in memory and cause problems at a later time.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] If detected, a soft error may be corrected by rewriting correct data in place of erroneous data.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Highly reliable systems use error correction to correct soft errors on the fly.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] However, in many systems, it may be impossible to determine the correct data, or even to discover that an error is present at all.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In addition, before the correction can occur, the system may have crashed, in which case the recovery procedure must include a reboot.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft errors involve changes to data‍—‌the electrons in a storage circuit, for example‍—‌but not changes to the physical circuit itself, the atoms.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] If the data is rewritten, the circuit will work perfectly again.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft errors can occur on transmission lines, in digital logic, analog circuits, magnetic storage, and elsewhere, but are most commonly known in semiconductor storage.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Whether or not a circuit experiences a soft error depends on the energy of the incoming particle, the geometry of the impact, the location of the strike, and the design of the logic circuit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Logic circuits with higher capacitance and higher logic voltages are less likely to suffer an error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This combination of capacitance and voltage is described by the *critical charge* parameter, Qcrit, the minimum electron charge disturbance needed to change the logic level.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Unfortunately, a higher Qcrit also means a slower logic gate and a higher power dissipation.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Reduction in chip feature size and supply voltage, desirable for many reasons, decreases Qcrit.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Thus, the importance of soft errors increases as chip technology advances.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In a logic circuit, Qcrit is defined as the minimum amount of induced charge required at a circuit node to cause a voltage pulse to propagate from that node to the output and be of sufficient duration and magnitude to be reliably latched.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Since a logic circuit contains many nodes that may be struck, and each node may be of unique capacitance and distance from output, Qcrit is typically characterized on a per-node basis.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft errors became widely known with the introduction of dynamic RAM in the 1970s.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In these early devices, ceramic chip packaging materials contained small amounts of radioactive contaminants.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Very low decay rates are needed to avoid excess soft errors, and chip companies have occasionally suffered problems with contamination ever since.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] It is extremely hard to maintain the material purity needed.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Controlling alpha particle emission rates for critical packaging materials to less than a level of 0.001 counts per hour per cm2 (cph/cm2) is required for reliable performance of most circuits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] For comparison, the count rate of a typical shoe's sole is between 0.1 and 10 cph/cm2.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Radioactive contamination of chip packages were documented to cause some UltraSPARC II-based Ultra Enterprise server crashes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In this case, the crashes were traced to SRAM chips in the external CPU cache.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Package radioactive decay usually causes a soft error by alpha particle emission.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The positive charged alpha particle travels through the semiconductor and disturbs the distribution of electrons there.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] If the disturbance is large enough, a digital signal can change from a 0 to a 1 or vice versa.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In combinational logic, this effect is transient, perhaps lasting a fraction of a nanosecond, and this has led to the challenge of soft errors in combinational logic mostly going unnoticed.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In sequential logic such as latches and RAM, even this transient upset can become stored for an indefinite time, to be read out later.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Thus, designers are usually much more aware of the problem in storage circuits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] A 2011 Black Hat paper discusses the real-life security implications of such bit-flips in the Internet's Domain Name System.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The paper found up to 3,434 incorrect requests per day due to bit-flip changes for various common domains.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Many of these bit-flips would probably be attributable to hardware problems, but some could be attributed to alpha particles.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] These bit-flip errors may be taken advantage of by malicious actors in the form of bitsquatting.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Isaac Asimov received a letter congratulating him on an accidental prediction of alpha-particle RAM errors in a 1950s novel.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Once the electronics industry had determined how to control package contaminants, it became clear that other causes were also at work.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Ziegler led a program of work at IBM which culminated in the publication of a number of papers (Ziegler and Lanford, 1979) demonstrating that cosmic rays also could cause soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Indeed, in modern devices, cosmic rays may be the predominant cause.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Although the primary particle of the cosmic ray does not generally reach the Earth's surface, it creates a shower of energetic secondary particles.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] At the Earth's surface approximately 95% of the particles capable of causing soft errors are energetic neutrons with the remainder composed of protons and pions.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] IBM estimated in 1996 that one error per month per 256 MiB of RAM was expected for a desktop computer.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This flux of energetic neutrons is typically referred to as "cosmic rays" in the soft error literature.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Neutrons are uncharged and cannot disturb a circuit on their own, but undergo neutron capture by the nucleus of an atom in a chip.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This process may result in the production of charged secondaries, such as alpha particles and oxygen nuclei, which can then cause soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] For the common reference location of 40.7° N, 74° W at sea level (New York City, NY, USA), the flux is approximately 14 neutrons/cm2/hour.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Burying a system in a cave reduces the rate of cosmic-ray-induced soft errors to a negligible level.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In the lower levels of the atmosphere, the flux increases by a factor of about 2.2 for every 1000 m (1.3 for every 1000 ft) increase in altitude above sea level.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Computers operated on top of mountains experience an order of magnitude higher rate of soft errors compared to sea level.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The rate of upsets in aircraft may be more than 300 times the sea level upset rate.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This is in contrast to package decay-induced soft errors, which do not change with location.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] As chip density increases, Intel expects the errors caused by cosmic rays to increase and become a limiting factor in design.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The average rate of cosmic-ray soft errors is *inversely* proportional to sunspot activity.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] That is, the average number of cosmic-ray soft errors decreases during the active portion of the sunspot cycle and increases during the quiet portion.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This counter-intuitive result occurs for two reasons.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The Sun does not generally produce cosmic ray particles with energy above 1 GeV that are capable of penetrating to the Earth's upper atmosphere and creating particle showers, so the changes in the solar flux do not directly influence the number of errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Further, the increase in the solar flux during an active sun period does have the effect of reshaping the Earth's magnetic field providing some additional shielding against higher energy cosmic rays, resulting in a decrease in the number of particles creating showers.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The effect is fairly small in any case resulting in a ±7% modulation of the energetic neutron flux in New York City.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] One experiment measured the soft error rate at the sea level to be 5,950 failures in time (FIT = failures per billion hours) per DRAM chip.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] When the same test setup was moved to an underground vault, shielded by over 50 feet (15 m) of rock that effectively eliminated all cosmic rays, zero soft errors were recorded.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In this test, all other causes of soft errors are too small to be measured, compared to the error rate caused by cosmic rays.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Energetic neutrons produced by cosmic rays may lose most of their kinetic energy and reach thermal equilibrium with their surroundings as they are scattered by materials.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The resulting neutrons are simply referred to as thermal neutrons and have an average kinetic energy of about 25 millielectron-volts at 25 °C.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Thermal neutrons are also produced by environmental radiation sources, including the decay of naturally occurring radioactive elements such as uranium and thorium.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The thermal neutron flux from sources other than cosmic-ray showers may still be noticeable in an underground location and an important contributor to soft errors for some circuits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Neutrons that have lost kinetic energy until they are in thermal equilibrium with their surroundings are an important cause of soft errors for some circuits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] At low energies many neutron capture reactions become much more probable and result in fission of certain materials creating charged secondaries as fission byproducts.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] For some circuits the capture of a thermal neutron by the nucleus of the 10B isotope of boron is particularly important.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This nuclear reaction is an efficient producer of an alpha particle, 7Li nucleus and gamma ray.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Either of the charged particles (alpha or 7Li) may cause a soft error if produced in very close proximity, approximately 5 μm, to a critical circuit node.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The capture cross section for 11B is 6 orders of magnitude smaller and does not contribute to soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Boron has been used in BPSG, the insulator in the interconnection layers of integrated circuits, particularly in the lowest one.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The inclusion of boron lowers the melt temperature of the glass providing better reflow and planarization characteristics.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In this application the glass is formulated with a boron content of 4% to 5% by weight.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Naturally occurring boron is 20% 10B with the remainder the 11B isotope.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft errors are caused by the high level of 10B in this critical lower layer of some older integrated circuit processes.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Boron-11, used at low concentrations as a p-type dopant, does not contribute to soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Integrated circuit manufacturers eliminated borated dielectrics by the time individual circuit components decreased in size to 150 nm, largely due to this problem.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In critical designs, depleted boron‍—‌consisting almost entirely of boron-11‍—‌is used, to avoid this effect and therefore to reduce the soft error rate.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Boron-11 is a by-product of the nuclear industry.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] For applications in medical electronic devices this soft error mechanism may be extremely important.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Neutrons are produced during high-energy cancer radiation therapy using photon beam energies above 10 MeV.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] These neutrons are moderated as they are scattered from the equipment and walls in the treatment room resulting in a thermal neutron flux that is about 40 million higher than the normal environmental neutron flux.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This high thermal neutron flux will generally result in a very high rate of soft errors and consequent circuit upset.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft errors can also be caused by random noise or signal integrity problems, such as inductive or capacitive crosstalk.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] However, in general, these sources represent a small contribution to the overall soft error rate when compared to radiation effects.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Thus, accessing data stored in DRAM causes memory cells to leak their charges and interact electrically, as a result of high cells density in modern memory, altering the content of nearby memory rows that actually were not addressed in the original memory access.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] A designer can attempt to minimize the rate of soft errors by judicious device design, choosing the right semiconductor, package and substrate materials, and the right device geometry.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Often, however, this is limited by the need to reduce device size and voltage, to increase operating speed and to reduce power dissipation.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The susceptibility of devices to upsets is described in the industry using the JEDEC JESD-89 standard.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] One technique that can be used to reduce the soft error rate in digital circuits is called radiation hardening.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This involves increasing the capacitance at selected circuit nodes in order to increase its effective Qcrit value.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This reduces the range of particle energies to which the logic value of the node can be upset.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Radiation hardening is often accomplished by increasing the size of transistors who share a drain/source region at the node.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Since the area and power overhead of radiation hardening can be restrictive to design, the technique is often applied selectively to nodes which are predicted to have the highest probability of resulting in soft errors if struck.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Tools and models that can predict which nodes are most vulnerable are the subject of past and current research in the area of soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] There has been work addressing soft errors in processor and memory resources using both hardware and software techniques.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Several research efforts addressed soft errors by proposing error detection and recovery via hardware-based redundant multi-threading.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] These approaches used special hardware to replicate an application execution to identify errors in the output, which increased hardware design complexity and cost including high performance overhead.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Software-based soft error tolerant schemes, on the other hand, are flexible and can be applied on commercial off-the-shelf microprocessors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Many works propose compiler-level instruction replication and result checking for soft error detection.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Designers can choose to accept that soft errors will occur, and design systems with appropriate error detection and correction to recover gracefully.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Typically, a semiconductor memory design might use forward error correction, incorporating redundant data into each word to create an error correcting code.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Alternatively, roll-back error correction can be used, detecting the soft error with an error-detecting code such as parity, and rewriting correct data from another source.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This technique is often used for write-through cache memories.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft errors in logic circuits are sometimes detected and corrected using the techniques of fault tolerant design.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] These often include the use of redundant circuitry or computation of data, and typically come at the cost of circuit area, decreased performance, and/or higher power consumption.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The concept of triple modular redundancy (TMR) can be employed to ensure very high soft-error reliability in logic circuits.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In this technique, three identical copies of a circuit compute on the same data in parallel and outputs are fed into majority voting logic, returning the value that occurred in at least two of three cases.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In this way, the failure of one circuit due to soft error is discarded assuming the other two circuits operated correctly.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In practice, however, few designers can afford the greater than 200% circuit area and power overhead required, so it is usually only selectively applied.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Another common concept to correct soft errors in logic circuits is temporal (or time) redundancy, in which one circuit operates on the same data multiple times and compares subsequent evaluations for consistency.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] This approach, however, often incurs performance overhead, area overhead (if copies of latches are used to store data), and power overhead, though is considerably more area-efficient than modular redundancy.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Traditionally, DRAM has had the most attention in the quest to reduce or work around soft errors, due to the fact that DRAM has comprised the majority-share of susceptible device surface area in desktop, and server computer systems (ref. the prevalence of ECC RAM in server computers).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Hard figures for DRAM susceptibility are hard to come by, and vary considerably across designs, fabrication processes, and manufacturers.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] 1980s technology 256 kilobit DRAMS could have clusters of five or six bits flip from a single alpha particle.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Modern DRAMs have much smaller feature sizes, so the deposition of a similar amount of charge could easily cause many more bits to flip.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The design of error detection and correction circuits is helped by the fact that soft errors usually are localised to a very small area of a chip.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Usually, only one cell of a memory is affected, although high energy events can cause a multi-cell upset.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Conventional memory layout usually places one bit of many different correction words adjacent on a chip.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] So, even a *multi-cell upset* leads to only a number of separate *single-bit upsets* in multiple correction words, rather than a *multi-bit upset* in a single correction word.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] So, an error correcting code needs only to cope with a single bit in error in each correction word in order to cope with all likely soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The term 'multi-cell' is used for upsets affecting multiple cells of a memory, whatever correction words those cells happen to fall in.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] 'Multi-bit' is used when multiple bits in a single correction word are in error.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The three natural masking effects in combinational logic that determine whether a single event upset (SEU) will propagate to become a soft error are electrical masking, logical masking, and temporal (or timing-window) masking.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] An SEU is *logically masked* if its propagation is blocked from reaching an output latch because off-path gate inputs prevent a logical transition of that gate's output.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] An SEU is *electrically masked* if the signal is attenuated by the electrical properties of gates on its propagation path such that the resulting pulse is of insufficient magnitude to be reliably latched.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] An SEU is *temporally masked* if the erroneous pulse reaches an output latch, but it does not occur close enough to when the latch is actually triggered to hold.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] If all three masking effects fail to occur, the propagated pulse becomes latched and the output of the logic circuit will be an erroneous value.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] In the context of circuit operation, this erroneous output value may be considered a soft error event.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] However, from a microarchitectural-level standpoint, the affected result may not change the output of the currently-executing program.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] For instance, the erroneous data could be overwritten before use, masked in subsequent logic operations, or simply never be used.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] If erroneous data does not affect the output of a program, it is considered to be an example of *microarchitectural masking*.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Soft error rate (SER) is the rate at which a device or system encounters or is predicted to encounter soft errors.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] It is typically expressed as either the number of failures-in-time (FIT) or mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The unit adopted for quantifying failures in time is called FIT, which is equivalent to one error per billion hours of device operation.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] MTBF is usually given in years of device operation; to put it into perspective, one FIT equals to approximately 1,000,000,000 / (24 × 365.25) = 114,077 times longer between errors than one-year MTBF.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] While many electronic systems have an MTBF that exceeds the expected lifetime of the circuit, the SER may still be unacceptable to the manufacturer or customer.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] For instance, many failures per million circuits due to soft errors can be expected in the field if the system does not have adequate soft error protection.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] The failure of even a few products in the field, particularly if catastrophic, can tarnish the reputation of the product and company that designed it.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Also, in safety- or cost-critical applications where the cost of system failure far outweighs the cost of the system itself, a 1% risk of soft error failure per lifetime may be too high to be acceptable to the customer.
[src:ecc-memory-embedded/soft-error] Therefore, it is advantageous to design for low SER when manufacturing a system in high-volume or requiring extremely high reliability.
